T1  - Diversity leadership multiculturalism: The challenge of the securitisation of Chinese migrants in Australia
AN  - 2193487901
AB  - The paper makes three claims. The first one is that despite the recent setbacks or the alleged failure of multiculturalism, Australia has advanced the idea and practice of multiculturalism through developing a diversity leadership programme that aims to attract and recruit different cultural and ethnic peoples into a variety of leadership positions. The second claim is that the securitisation of Chinese migrants or Chinese‐Australians has a negative impact on diversity leadership multiculturalism. This is a worrying trend, but it is not a serious concern among security experts at all. The third claim is that diversity leadership multiculturalism can offer a fresh approach or strategy to dealing with both human and national security through defending the equality and rights of minorities and migrants. As a security instrument, multicultural policies and practices are the best means to win over the hearts and minds of migrants. This in turn aids democratic processes on a national scale and hence helps to bolster national security. In consideration of these three claims, this paper also explores the normative implications of Kymlick's theory of desecuritisation: the prioritising of cultural diversity and meritocracy without being compromised by colour or race; the upholding of the equality principle in returning to a democratic norm; and the revising of the sequence of desecuritisation prior to the development of multiculturalism. While multiculturalism has been well maintained in Australia, and free speech is held up as an entrenched part of Australian society, as it should be in any democracy, I should also acknowledge that security concerns on the threat from China, in particular on actual and potential Chinese influence in Australia is a legitimate one. Nevertheless, as Kymlicka (2010, pp.106‒107) correctly points out, “the securitisation of ethnic relations erodes both the democratic space to voice minority demands and the likelihood that those demands will be accepted”. This paper will illustrate and highlight the mechanisms of this erosion through the case of Australia.
